	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>WTO Ministerial: a forum for small trade concessions </h1>

			
			<h4>
												16 January 2012
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>Although the WTO Ministerial meeting of 15–17 December) failed to break the log-jam on the Doha Development Round, participants took the opportunity to agree in a non-binding and bilateral/plurilateral fashion a number of policy changes that could benefit the agricultural trade of some ACP states. One development, highlighted by Director-General Pascal Lamy in a briefing to reporters on the last day, was that African cotton exporters had received new commitments on market access and development assistance which ‘were not previously part of the landscape’.</p><p>A second development was that a number of ministers echoed the proposal of the G20 Heads of Government in November 2011 (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Commodities/General/The-G20-Summit-and-a-regional-approach-in-West-Africa-to-food-security-and-price-volatility" target="_blank">The G20 Summit and a regional approach in West Africa to food security a...</a>’,&nbsp; 19 December 2011) that Members should avoid imposing export restrictions on food aid purchased by the World Food Programme.</p><p>Also on food security issues, the chair’s statement reflected support among some ministers for a WTO ‘work programme’ on trade and food price volatility and its impact on LDCs and net food-importing developing countries.</p><p>None of these commitments are binding, but constitute best-endeavour commitments of a range of members.</p><p>One change which could have an indirect effect on agriculture and food security, and which is now written (temporarily) into the WTO’s rules, relates to the waiver that allows countries to grant preferences to LDCs on trade in services. The waiver does not require any Member to do so and nor does it indicate the type of preference that could be useful. But it clarifies that, should a country offer preferences, these would not be illegal in the WTO (at least for the 15-year duration of the waiver).</p><p>Given that a significant part of the value of ‘trade in goods’ is actually payment for services, this could have an indirect effect on the agricultural sectors of some ACP states.</p><p>The Geneva Ministerial will however have a lasting and substantial effect on at least one ACP country, namely Samoa, whose membership of the WTO was formally approved by the WTO membership at the December 2011 meeting. Samoa will now become a WTO member 30 days after the government of Samoa has ratified the accession agreement. Vanuatu had its application for WTO membership agreed prior to the Ministerial meeting.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>ICTSD, ‘WTO Ministerial conference: Chair gavels decisions, maps out &nbsp;future’ / ‘Conférence ministérielle de l’OMC : Le président entérine les décisions prises et dresse les plans pour l’avenir, update on the WTO 3-day Ministerial meeting and outcomes, <i>Bridges/Passerelles</i>, 18 December 2011</p><p>
<a href="http://ictsd.org/i/wto/geneva2011/bridges-daily-updates-geneva-2011/122583/" target="_self">http://ictsd.org/i/wto/geneva2011/bridges-daily-updates-geneva-2011/122583/</a></p><p>
<a href="http://ictsd.org/i/wto/geneva2011/passerelles-mise-a-jour-geneve-2011/122596/" target="_self">http://ictsd.org/i/wto/geneva2011/passerelles-mise-a-jour-geneve-2011/12...</a></p><p><i>WTO News</i>, ‘WTO ministers adopt waiver to permit preferential treatment of LDC service suppliers’, 17 December 2011</p><p>
<a href="http://www.wto.org/english/news_e/news11_e/serv_17dec11_e.htm" target="_self">http://www.wto.org/english/news_e/news11_e/serv_17dec11_e.htm</a></p><p><i>WTO News</i>, ‘Day 3: Samoa and Montenegro join Russia with membership agreed, as ministers wrap up conference’, 17 December 2011</p><p>
<a href="http://www.wto.org/english/news_e/news11_e/mn11a_17dec11_e.htm" target="_self">http://www.wto.org/english/news_e/news11_e/mn11a_17dec11_e.htm</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>While vocal and influential on issues of particular importance, the ACP are largely bystanders on the big issues that continue to block completion of the Doha Round. ICTSD has reported that ‘long-standing disagreements between developed economies - such as the US and EU - and major emerging economies - such as Brazil, China, and India - on non-agricultural and agricultural market access have widely been faulted for putting the negotiations on hold.’ Unless and until these big issues are resolved, ACP states can only seek improvements in their trade position within the WTO forum through informal negotiation. Such informal negotiations may bear some fruit, but they are inherently partial and non-binding.</p><p>In the meantime, like all other Members, they have to take a view on whether or not &nbsp; new issues should be discussed within the WTO forum. There are fears that this is a route whereby some countries are seeking to introduce issues that are of high concern for them, but which have not been agreed as part of the Doha Agenda. This shifts the focus away from items on the existing agenda that are of concern to poorer, more vulnerable developing countries. Others argue that ‘talking’ is not the same as ‘negotiating’ and that if the WTO fails to do even the former it will become increasingly irrelevant to the major trade challenges facing the world economy.</p>
		</div>
		
